sub_title: Knit researcher, Footwear innovator & Founder of Knit in Motion [KiM]
summary:
I am a knit developer, technician, and designer specialising in footwear, and the founder of Knit in Motion [KiM]. KiM is a knit development and consultancy studio which shares my vision and values of research and experimentation. Both at KiM and in my personal research, I strive to recontextualise knitting and use it as a tool to solve problems around footwear construction and manufacturing methods. 

Since 2016, I have worked with brands such as, Rothy’s and On Running and participated in numerous collaborations between industries, including Timberland Construct 10061 and Takashi Murakami x Complexcon “Sneakers for Breakfast”.

A fascination with materials and play has fuelled my approach to textile and material design since studying Product Design at ArtEZ University of the Arts, Arnhem [2015]. It was there that I first saw potential in the ways in which knitted textiles could be applied to footwear. My playful and inquisitive approach has always led me to question, research and push boundaries.

Through working as a technician at the TextielMuseum [2018-2021]  I have been able to explore my unique perspectives and gain more technical expertise by programming and operating the latest Stoll knitting technologies. As a result, I have adopted a hybrid approach to knit development where I am a designer, knit engineer and product developer. This unique way of working carries over to KiM, where experimentation is balanced by technical skills.
